<div id="review_3867363002" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3867363002" />
    <a title="Dylan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/53637835-dylan"><img alt="Dylan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1582434207p2/53637835.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3867363002?book_show_action=true">Mar 01, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dylan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dylan" href="/user/show/53637835-dylan">Dylan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/53637835-dylan?shelf=science-fiction">science-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3867363002" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9371926462196231044"><b> 8.5/10? </b> <br/><br/>If you want to know my thoughts on SOTT, this will serve as an extension to that review here. <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3810338383?book_show_action=false&amp;from_review_page=1%20' rel='nofollow noopener'> The Shadow of the Torturer Review </a><br/><br/><blockquote> <b> “I believe there is no other difference between those who are called courageous and those who are branded craven than that the second are fearful before the danger and the first after it. No one can be much frightened, certainly, during a period of great and imminent peril -- the mind is too much concentrated on the thing itself, and on the actions necessar</b></blockquote></span>
  <span id="freeText9371926462196231044" style="display:none"><b> 8.5/10? </b> <br /><br />If you want to know my thoughts on SOTT, this will serve as an extension to that review here. <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3810338383?book_show_action=false&amp;from_review_page=1%20" rel="nofollow noopener"> The Shadow of the Torturer Review </a><br /><br /><blockquote> <b> “I believe there is no other difference between those who are called courageous and those who are branded craven than that the second are fearful before the danger and the first after it. No one can be much frightened, certainly, during a period of great and imminent peril -- the mind is too much concentrated on the thing itself, and on the actions necessary to meet or avoid it. The coward is a coward, then, because he has brought his fear with him; persons we think cowardly will sometimes amaze us by their bravery, if they have had no forewarning of their danger.” </b> </blockquote> <br /> <br /><b> Introduction </b> <br /><br />Shadow of the Torturer is like a cyclical dream its both a fantastic and strange foundation. COTT manages to follow that up thankfully to even more bizarre territory. I would state, scoring still uncertain until I got the big picture. For me, it lives up to the promise of the original. Which I will talk about in this review. But I will have to say I think this book truly lives up to the hype, in terms of its placement in Sci-Fi truly I do not think I will read something like this ever again.<br /><br />Anyways SOTT was more just the first part of a book, it being the Fellowship of the Rings. This novel is like the first half of the Two Towers. Most arcs aren't complete though they are some but minimal indeed few most are still developing. Severian has been growing in interesting ways throughout the journey pretty much all of it unexpectedly. This probably the most difficult book to even predict you play a fool's game in doing so but an interesting game.<br /><br />Like Shadow of the Torturer, I have written a shit ton of notes, but it will excessively destroy this word count if I even attempt to publish it. Anyways on the topic, I was deciding is this review even warranted to a degree I stated in SOTT that I don’t think I going to do another review which is half true this will be more extension of my prior review because I don’t think repeating the praise is necessary but the distinctive factors I will talk about right now. Again, the scoring going to be somewhat irrelevant because only read half of a book so far (SOTT and COTC included). In this review, I will be examining the writing, worldbuilding, characters, few notable flaws and my final remarks. This review will be a non-spoiler with spoiler sections throughout tagged.<br /><br /><br /><b> Story </b> <br /><br />You read the ending of the SOTT and your like okay I need some answers well you have both some answers and none. Though the answers filled with so much obscurity trying to wrap your mind in what happened in the SOTT ending is a guessing game. <br /><br />Anyways if I were talking about the plot here I go:<br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ Severian and Jonas are in the village Saltus, trying to make money so they can meet Dr Talos and decides to Execute few people. Firstly, their this innocent lady which brings an important part in Severian life … as this is the first time he executed a proven innocent person. He basically must rationalise what the action he vomits, he guilty etc for what he conducted was not justice. Which is the first time Severian has considered that. Which is a great contrast where he put into the same position in killing Agia which he technically has a good reason she attempted to murder him twice at this point. But he spared her showcasing this Mercy. <br />Oh yeah before the Agia incident he meets a green man from the future and it's fascinating to explore. Seeing the sun is so grow in his world that he can have nutrients and everything from his body like Photosynthesis basically, again they this funny Severian maturing as a person. In the incident before Agia, you also get a flashback with Master Gurloes which does bring into question his perspective on women. The dude never saw women as people from a young age plus he never viewed sex for pleasure but as a tool for rape which the torturers use which has some fucked up implication.<br /><br /><br />Anyways Severian learns he must execute a spy of Vodalus but gets taken by a couple of cutthroats to meet Vodalus which finally the big plot is described to us. Why Vodalus doing what he is doing, whats this rebellion and wtf with the volunteers well you understand why they exist. From the entire SOTT to now Sev has deluded himself in think that Vodalus remember him and knew him. Thinking fantasies like oh he will rescue me from this tower when he helped Thecla kill herself. My favourite moment in this meeting because this couple chapters it terms of admiring Vod to completely despising him in contempt. Because Severian must eat Thecla, which brings an interesting relationship at a metaphysical level. The Severian we knew is dead this is now a completely different person. The person who is writing this novel is not Severian it is a merging of Thecla and Severian as one person. This is where Severian mannerisms change both in subtle and explicit ways. He a lot more proper and I think understand guilty which I mean he revived that patrolling soldier for a reason. He feels more Remorseful than ever. Anyways he gets captured and goes to the Antechamber basically what was originally a holiday house or something and House of absolute is like a giant space bunker underground ironically enough. We do see another side of Thecla in here basically she used to tease these prisoners down here… who been entrapped for centuries. Anyways they escape through a secret entrance and Jonas is like I’m out of here like a boss and escapes through a mirror teleportation device through dimensions. You know the most confusing chapter in SOTT ch20 well here this is a different context and that is used more in this novel like the ending of this book or even when he meets the Autarch. <br /><br /><br />Anyways he escapes the Autarch and meets his troupe and.  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> this is where this loses a lot of people. Because chapter 23+24 is too much for a lot of people in many ways it's perfectly understandable. They certain explicit content done in chapter 23 which makes you think certain characters changed but unfortunately, they haven’t in many ways. Anyways after that what worse is chapter 24 shit simply the hardest chapter I’ve read in my entire life. It's not even poorly written kinda hard right. Like difficult chapters can merely poorly communicate or badly written this I cannot make that excuse. It's just so many narratives inside a narrative in COTT as a whole bunch more than SOTT or just harder to grasp which makes this such a loop. As there 5 people playing a minimum of 20 people, replicating a real-life play. Its such a flex on Gene Wolfe part in depicting it feeling realistic but god damn hard to grasp. Anyways the chapter I got the central theme basically <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ like the title of the play is death and beginning ( death and rebirth). Which the old sun dies with the old Urth and the New Sun arises to cleanse the Urth.  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> but they do many aspects you feel like you have lost. Anyways all this shit is done and onwards it's basically the aftermath and mans it's truly interesting and wild. The Weird aspects are cranked up to another level. Though compared to SOTT I like the ending better here even though it's a complete mind blown moment.<br /><br /><br /><b> Writing </b> <br /><br />It's even more dreamlike and at points, it has truly higher than SOTT like chapter 11 was the dread and atmosphere was liking magic. The stories within stories are such a flex like a mashup of mythologies which such makes an interesting read like chapter 17. It is a mix of Theseus and the naval Battle of Hampton Roads that something you get straight away. But once you realise you realise oh shit regarding the meta-aspects. I know the books just get weirder; I am sure curious how far can it go. Anyways if you love the writing of SOTT the same quality all around but even more surreal.<br /><br /><br /><b> Worldbuilding</b> <br /><br />The worldbuilding sometimes explicit, other times its something you have to unpack its rewards you paying attention. Like so many animals you meet which are most likely extinct or a certain species called something for Severian POV but someone else in the story calls it something else which is just funny as hell. Even the stories within stories tell you to want to happen to history and myth how they merged. You get a rough idea of what the world is like outside of Urth. You explore more species is an interesting way they a particular alien species which is mindfucking. Which is used in chapter 11 those who read it already knew. But yeah that chapter, in general, makes you reflect on the entire novel as a whole, why the people do certain things at night.<br /><br /><b> Characters</b> <br /><br />The character work is just great, certain things unravelled which have made you rethink the entire series even SOTT. How certain things are addressed. If you like the character work in SOTT the same will remain, what's most interesting how the side characters develop. What initially portrayed one dimensional or simple has a lot more than meets the eye this is true for two people. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ Baldanders and Talos being the reverse Frankenstein that Baldanders being the master despite how Severian perceive them initially  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>. They a lot of characters that are extremely well developed but it takes too much time to dive into them. But all I will say they more than meet the eye. <br /><br /><br /><b> Flaws</b> <br /><br />Talked about in kinda in my story section. But sometimes its too vague for its own good, which I mean I loved it but I can see other people disliking it. This is not a flaw but a protagonist being unlikable can be a turn-off and Severian does certain things you simply can’t defend him. You find him an interesting and complex character but he, not someone you should relate to by any means. If you dislike morally grey characters this ain't the series for you. As pretty much all the characters aren’t really good people with the exception of like Dorcas and few others.<br /><br /><br /><b> Conclusion </b> <br /><br />Considering the extensive notes I’ve done for the series I don’t have the urge to plus its hard to review something of this nature as its 2/4 a novel ( in total). So I don’t have the overall picture yet, anyways if you love SOTT do check this out and continue this journey of Severian's extraordinary and triply place. Its awesome buddy reading this novel with someone has been great discussing it as I read this heavy read. If I were to score it still be a question mark:<br /><b> 8.5/10? </b></span>
  <a data-text-id="9371926462196231044" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


